// Endocrinology chapter — extracted from a dense multi-topic endocrinology course summary
// (pituitary/hypothalamic axes, adrenal, thyroid, neuroendocrine tumors, calcium/bone,
// type 2 diabetes, and obesity). Quiz items carry an optional `ref` field — the index into
// that topic's own `flashcards` array that the question is grounded in — used by the app's
// "View in Reference" deep link.
const ENDO_TOPICS = [
{
  id: "endo-pituitary-physiology",
  name: "Hypothalamic-Pituitary Axes & Hypopituitarism",
  blurb: "The six hypothalamic-pituitary hormone axes, and how their combined or sequential failure presents.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"In the thyroid axis, what is the hormone, its activator, and its suppressor?", back:"Hormone: TSH. Activator: TRH. Suppressor: somatostatin. TSH induces T3/T4 secretion, which in turn inhibits further TSH production (a negative feedback loop)."},
    {front:"What distinguishes primary from secondary hypothyroidism on labs?", back:"Primary hypothyroidism: low T3/T4 with a high TSH and TRH (e.g. autoimmune Hashimoto's, post-thyroidectomy). Secondary hypothyroidism: low T3/T4 with a low TSH and TRH (a pituitary/hypothalamic problem)."},
    {front:"What distinguishes primary from secondary hyperthyroidism on labs?", back:"Primary hyperthyroidism: high T3/T4 with a low-to-undetectable TSH (e.g. autoimmune Graves' disease, toxic goiter). Secondary hyperthyroidism: caused by a TSH-secreting tumor."},
    {front:"In the gonadal axis, what are the hormones, and how does GnRH pulsatility affect them?", back:"FSH and LH, regulated by GnRH. Pulsatile GnRH secretion is activating (stimulates FSH/LH release), while constant/continuous GnRH exposure is repressive (downregulates the axis)."},
    {front:"What are the symptoms of hypogonadism?", back:"Delayed sexual development, amenorrhea, infertility, and osteoporosis."},
    {front:"In the adrenal axis, what is the hormone and its activator, and what else can trigger the activator?", back:"Hormone: ACTH. Activator: CRH. CRH release can also be triggered by vasopressin."},
    {front:"What are the symptoms of hypoadrenalism?", back:"Weakness, vomiting, weight loss, stomach aches, and hyponatremia."},
    {front:"How do primary and secondary hypoadrenalism differ clinically?", back:"Primary: high ACTH with hyperpigmentation. Secondary: reduced androgen-driven hair growth and adrenal atrophy in chronic cases, without the ACTH-driven hyperpigmentation seen in primary disease."},
    {front:"What is \"subclinical hypoadrenalism,\" and when does it become apparent?", back:"A state where adrenal reserve is reduced but adequate for baseline needs — it only becomes symptomatic during acute medical stress, when extra reserve capacity is needed and unavailable."},
    {front:"What are three tests used to evaluate the adrenal axis, and what do they show?", back:"ACTH stimulation test (only secondary adrenal insufficiency responds/improves); insulin-induced hypoglycemia (should activate cortisol secretion via the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis); metyrapone test (inhibits 11-hydroxylase, a step in cortisol synthesis — an intact axis should respond by increasing upstream activity once cortisol's negative feedback is removed)."},
    {front:"In the growth hormone axis, what is the hormone, its activator, and its suppressor, and what are its deficiency symptoms?", back:"Hormone: GH. Activator: GHRH. Suppressor: somatostatin. Deficiency causes growth arrest in children, and loss of muscle mass, weakness, and malaise in adults."},
    {front:"What normally regulates prolactin secretion, and what happens with any hypothalamic-pituitary axis disruption?", back:"Prolactin is under constant tonic suppression by dopamine; any disruption of the hypothalamic-pituitary connection (e.g. a mass compressing the pituitary stalk) removes this suppression and raises prolactin levels."},
    {front:"What triggers vasopressin release, and via which receptors?", back:"High blood osmolarity (via V2 receptors) or hypotension (via V1a receptors), released from the neurohypophysis (posterior pituitary)."},
    {front:"List the recognized causes of hypopituitarism.", back:"Congenital (rare mutations in organogenesis/transcription-factor genes — PROP1, PIT1, KAL1, GPR54, T-PIT); acquired (tumors, trauma, pituitary necrosis/Sheehan syndrome postpartum, granulomatous disease); and irradiation-induced (during brain tumor treatment, with a gradual, sequential effect)."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"A patient has low T3/T4 with a high TSH and high TRH. What does this pattern indicate?", options:["Primary hypothyroidism","Secondary hypothyroidism","Primary hyperthyroidism","Secondary hyperthyroidism"], answer:0, explain:"Primary hypothyroidism (e.g. Hashimoto's, post-thyroidectomy) shows low T3/T4 with a compensatory rise in TSH and TRH.", ref:1},
    {q:"Which pattern of GnRH secretion activates the gonadal axis, versus which pattern represses it?", options:["Pulsatile secretion activates; constant/continuous secretion represses","Constant secretion activates; pulsatile secretion represses","Both patterns activate the axis equally","Neither pattern affects axis activity"], answer:0, explain:"Pulsatile GnRH stimulates FSH/LH release, while continuous, non-pulsatile GnRH exposure downregulates the axis — the basis for GnRH-agonist suppression therapy.", ref:3},
    {q:"Which adrenal axis test relies on inhibiting 11-hydroxylase to demonstrate an intact negative feedback loop?", options:["Metyrapone test","ACTH stimulation test","Insulin-induced hypoglycemia test","Dexamethasone suppression test"], answer:0, explain:"Metyrapone inhibits 11-hydroxylase (a step in cortisol synthesis); in an intact axis, removing cortisol's negative feedback should increase upstream axis activity.", ref:9},
    {q:"Why does hypopituitarism from irradiation typically affect hormone axes in a gradual, sequential way?", options:["It has a gradual effect over the course of treatment, rather than affecting all axes simultaneously and completely","It affects all axes simultaneously and completely from the start","It only ever affects the TSH axis","It affects the adrenal axis before any other axis, always completely"], answer:0, explain:"Irradiation-induced hypopituitarism during brain tumor treatment has a gradual effect on pituitary function rather than an abrupt, complete failure of every axis at once.", ref:13},
    {q:"What removes the normal suppression of prolactin secretion, leading to elevated prolactin levels?", options:["Any disruption of the hypothalamic-pituitary connection that interrupts dopamine's tonic inhibition","Increased TRH secretion only","Increased somatostatin secretion","Increased vasopressin secretion"], answer:0, explain:"Prolactin is normally under constant dopamine-mediated suppression; disrupting the hypothalamic-pituitary connection (e.g. stalk compression) removes this suppression and raises prolactin.", ref:11}
  ]
},
{
  id: "endo-di-siadh",
  name: "Diabetes Insipidus & SIADH",
  blurb: "Central vs. nephrogenic DI vs. primary polydipsia, and SIADH — differentiating causes of abnormal water handling.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"What is diabetes insipidus (DI)?", back:"Excessive secretion of hypotonic (dilute) urine due to renal or hypothalamic-pituitary disease."},
    {front:"What causes central DI, and what is the treatment?", back:"Genetic mutations (e.g. pre-provasopressin gene mutations), malignancy (usually metastatic), surgery, or irradiation affecting vasopressin production/release; treated with desmopressin."},
    {front:"What is (primary/psychogenic) polydipsia, in the DI differential?", back:"A psychogenic phenomenon of excessive water consumption — the primary problem is excess intake rather than a defect in the kidney's urine-concentrating ability."},
    {front:"How is a water (thirst) deprivation test used to distinguish the causes of DI, and what does each pattern show?", back:"Water is withheld for a prolonged period, then urine osmolality and the response to desmopressin are checked. Central DI: urine osmolality is low and rises (concentrates) with desmopressin. Nephrogenic DI: urine osmolality stays low even after desmopressin. Primary polydipsia: urine osmolality rises with fluid restriction but plateaus below the normal maximum (from chronic medullary washout) and does not rise further with desmopressin. Partial DI: urine osmolality rises partially and spontaneously, and desmopressin increases it further."},
    {front:"What is SIADH, and what must be excluded before attributing it to an ectopic source?", back:"Ectopic secretion of ADH, classically from a neuroendocrine tumor; hypoadrenalism and hypothyroidism must be ruled out as alternative causes of the same biochemical picture first."},
    {front:"What is the primary treatment for SIADH?", back:"Fluid (water) restriction."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"During a water deprivation test, urine osmolality remains low despite administering desmopressin. What is the diagnosis?", options:["Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus","Central diabetes insipidus","Primary polydipsia","Partial diabetes insipidus"], answer:0, explain:"Nephrogenic DI fails to concentrate urine even with exogenous desmopressin, since the defect is renal unresponsiveness to ADH rather than a lack of ADH.", ref:3},
    {q:"A patient's urine osmolality rises with water deprivation but plateaus below the normal maximum, without further increase after desmopressin. What is the diagnosis?", options:["Primary (psychogenic) polydipsia","Central diabetes insipidus","Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus","SIADH"], answer:0, explain:"Chronic excess water intake causes medullary washout, so the kidney cannot reach a normal maximal concentration even with fluid restriction, and ADH signaling itself is intact so desmopressin adds nothing further.", ref:3},
    {q:"Before diagnosing SIADH as due to ectopic ADH secretion, which two conditions must be excluded as the underlying cause?", options:["Hypoadrenalism and hypothyroidism","Hyperthyroidism and hyperadrenalism","Type 2 diabetes and osteoporosis","Acromegaly and prolactinoma"], answer:0, explain:"Hypoadrenalism and hypothyroidism can both produce a SIADH-like picture and must be excluded before attributing it to ectopic ADH secretion.", ref:4},
    {q:"What is the treatment for SIADH?", options:["Fluid (water) restriction","Desmopressin administration","A thiazide diuretic","A high-salt diet with liberal water intake"], answer:0, explain:"SIADH is treated with water restriction, since the underlying problem is excess free water retention relative to solute.", ref:5}
  ]
},
{
  id: "endo-pituitary-tumors",
  name: "Pituitary Tumors",
  blurb: "Pituitary adenomas by cell lineage — acromegaly, prolactinoma, Cushing disease, non-functioning tumors, and craniopharyngioma.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"How are pituitary adenomas classified by size, and what is the general term for most pituitary tumors?", back:"Most pituitary tumors are monoclonal pituitary adenomas, classified as microadenomas (<10mm) or macroadenomas (>10mm)."},
    {front:"Which pituitary cell lineage secretes GH, TSH, and prolactin?", back:"The PIT1 lineage."},
    {front:"What is the difference between gigantism and acromegaly?", back:"Both are caused by GH-secreting adenomas; gigantism occurs in children (before growth plate closure), while acromegaly occurs in adults (affecting mostly soft tissue) and causes hypertension, cardiovascular disease, obstructive sleep apnea, colonic polyps, and thyroid cysts."},
    {front:"What is the underlying pathophysiology of most GH-secreting adenomas, and what rare familial syndromes are associated?", back:"A GPCR driver mutation causing continuous signaling activation; rare cases are associated with familial syndromes such as MEN1 or NF1."},
    {front:"How is acromegaly diagnosed?", back:"A glucose overload (oral glucose tolerance test) should suppress GH levels physiologically but fails to do so in acromegaly; IGF-1 levels can also be reviewed, as they reflect integrated GH activity."},
    {front:"What is the treatment approach for acromegaly?", back:"Transsphenoidal surgery to normalize IGF-1 and GH; medical therapy follows a stepwise approach — 1st line: somatostatin analogs (octreotide, lanreotide); 2nd line: dopamine agonists; 3rd line: GH receptor antagonist or irradiation."},
    {front:"What is the typical epidemiology and size of prolactinomas, and how does high prolactin cause symptoms?", back:"Very common in young women, usually as microadenomas; high prolactin suppresses FSH and LH, causing oligomenorrhea and sexual dysfunction."},
    {front:"How does macroprolactinoma epidemiology differ from microprolactinoma, and what does its presence suggest?", back:"Macroprolactinoma is more common in men, and its presence is itself a sign favoring a true prolactin-secreting adenoma over other causes of hyperprolactinemia."},
    {front:"What is the differential diagnosis for hyperprolactinemia besides a prolactinoma?", back:"Pregnancy, stress, drugs (antipsychotics, antidepressants, antiemetics, cocaine, opiates), and non-adenoma malignancies."},
    {front:"What is the treatment for prolactinoma?", back:"1st line: dopamine agonists (bromocriptine, cabergoline). Surgery is reserved mainly for microadenomas not controlled medically."},
    {front:"How common are TSH-secreting pituitary tumors, and what is notable about co-secretion and treatment?", back:"Very rare, mostly macroadenomas; in some cases they co-secrete GH and prolactin. Treatment: surgery, somatostatin analogs, and irradiation."},
    {front:"What causes Cushing disease (as opposed to Cushing syndrome broadly), and what is the typical tumor size?", back:"Central hyperadrenalism from a pituitary corticotroph adenoma, typically a very small microadenoma, associated with mutations in USP8 (a ubiquitin-degrading enzyme acting on GPCRs)."},
    {front:"What is the classic symptom complex of Cushing syndrome?", back:"Moon face, weight gain, proximal muscle weakness, and new or worsened diabetes and hypertension."},
    {front:"How is Cushing disease diagnosed?", back:"Assessing ACTH dependency, a negative-feedback (dexamethasone suppression) test, and imaging; inferior petrosal sinus sampling (IPSS) is the gold standard, catheterizing both petrosal sinuses to measure ACTH and detect a central-to-peripheral gradient."},
    {front:"What is the treatment approach for Cushing disease, and what can happen afterward?", back:"Surgery, irradiation, and in severe cases adrenalectomy; medical options include a somatostatin analog (pasireotide), dopamine agonists, ketoconazole (blocks steroidogenesis), other steroidogenesis enzyme inhibitors, and glucocorticoid receptor blockers. Post-treatment patients may experience hypoadrenalism and require monitoring/replacement."},
    {front:"What are non-functioning pituitary tumors, and what do they typically present with?", back:"About 75% are gonadotroph-lineage tumors (gonadotropinomas). They cause nonspecific mass-effect signs (headache, visual/eye pathology) rather than a clear hormone-excess syndrome, though some cause multiple ovarian cysts in women or elevated testosterone in men. Treatment is surgical."},
    {front:"What is a craniopharyngioma, and what are its two histologic subtypes?", back:"An epithelial tumor common in children, mostly benign; the adamantinomatous subtype carries a beta-catenin mutation, while the papillary subtype carries a BRAF mutation and occurs mostly in adults."},
    {front:"What are the symptoms of craniopharyngioma?", back:"Growth arrest, headaches, impaired vision, diabetes insipidus, and hypothalamic obesity."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"A patient's GH level fails to suppress after an oral glucose load, and IGF-1 is elevated. What is the diagnosis, and what is first-line medical therapy if surgery alone is insufficient?", options:["Acromegaly; somatostatin analogs (e.g. octreotide, lanreotide)","Prolactinoma; dopamine agonists","Cushing disease; ketoconazole","A non-functioning adenoma; observation"], answer:0, explain:"Failure of GH to suppress with a glucose load plus elevated IGF-1 is diagnostic of acromegaly/GH excess; first-line medical therapy after surgery is a somatostatin analog.", ref:4},
    {q:"A young woman has oligomenorrhea and a small pituitary microadenoma with elevated prolactin. What is the first-line treatment?", options:["A dopamine agonist (e.g. cabergoline or bromocriptine)","Transsphenoidal surgery","A somatostatin analog","Radioactive iodine"], answer:0, explain:"Prolactinoma is treated first-line with dopamine agonists; surgery is reserved mainly for microadenomas that fail medical therapy, or macroadenomas with mass effect.", ref:9},
    {q:"What is the gold-standard test for localizing ACTH to a pituitary source in suspected Cushing disease?", options:["Inferior petrosal sinus sampling (IPSS)","A single midnight cortisol level","Chromogranin A","A 24-hour urine catecholamine collection"], answer:0, explain:"IPSS catheterizes both petrosal sinuses to measure ACTH and detect a central-to-peripheral gradient, confirming a pituitary source.", ref:13},
    {q:"What is the most common lineage of non-functioning pituitary tumors, and their typical presentation?", options:["Gonadotroph lineage (about 75%); nonspecific mass-effect symptoms like headache and visual disturbance","Corticotroph lineage; Cushing syndrome","Somatotroph lineage; acromegaly","Lactotroph lineage; galactorrhea"], answer:0, explain:"About 75% of non-functioning pituitary tumors are gonadotroph-lineage (gonadotropinomas), typically presenting with nonspecific mass-effect symptoms rather than a hormone-excess syndrome.", ref:15},
    {q:"A child has growth arrest, headaches, and diabetes insipidus. Imaging shows a suprasellar epithelial mass, and pathology shows a beta-catenin mutation. What is the diagnosis?", options:["Adamantinomatous craniopharyngioma","Papillary craniopharyngioma","Prolactinoma","A non-functioning gonadotropinoma"], answer:0, explain:"Craniopharyngioma is common in children; the adamantinomatous subtype carries a beta-catenin mutation, while the papillary subtype (BRAF-mutated) occurs mostly in adults.", ref:16}
  ]
},
{
  id: "endo-adrenal-insufficiency",
  name: "Adrenal Insufficiency & Incidentalomas",
  blurb: "Addison's disease, its diagnosis and stress-dosing, and how to characterize an incidentally found adrenal nodule.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"What are the causes of primary adrenal insufficiency (Addison's disease)?", back:"Mostly autoimmune; also infectious (TB, HIV), malignancy, and drug-induced (e.g. ketoconazole)."},
    {front:"What causes secondary adrenal insufficiency, and why does it tend to present later than primary disease?", back:"Hypothalamic (low CRH) or pituitary (low ACTH) disease; it usually presents at a later stage of pituitary failure since corticotroph (ACTH-producing) cells are among the last cell types to be affected."},
    {front:"Why does hyperpigmentation occur only in primary (not secondary) adrenal insufficiency?", back:"In primary disease, high ACTH also raises melanocyte-stimulating hormone (from the same POMC precursor), causing hyperpigmentation; in secondary disease ACTH is low, so this does not occur."},
    {front:"Why do patients with primary adrenal insufficiency crave salt?", back:"Diffuse adrenal damage also reduces aldosterone secretion, causing hyponatremia and a salt-craving response."},
    {front:"Why are random cortisol levels non-specific for diagnosing adrenal insufficiency, and when should testing be timed?", back:"Cortisol follows a dynamic circadian pattern, so a single random level is hard to interpret; testing should be done in the early morning, when cortisol normally peaks."},
    {front:"What is a normal post-stimulation cortisol level on an ACTH stimulation test, and what does the insulin tolerance test (ITT) assess?", back:"A normal response is above about 18-20 mcg% (550 nmol/L). The ITT uses insulin-induced hypoglycemia to activate the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis and raise cortisol; its main risk is that the induced hypoglycemia itself can be life-threatening, so it is used less today."},
    {front:"What is the standard treatment for adrenal insufficiency, and how should dosing change with illness?", back:"Exogenous glucocorticoids — hydrocortisone (1st line, 20-30mg/day divided 2-3 times), prednisone (2nd line, 5mg once daily), and fludrocortisone/Florinef (for isolated mineralocorticoid deficiency). Dosing should increase with stress: roughly 2-3 fold for minor stress (e.g. fever >38°C), and about 10-fold for major stress (surgery/medical emergencies)."},
    {front:"Why must withdrawal from long-term exogenous steroids be gradual, and how is readiness to stop confirmed?", back:"Chronic exogenous glucocorticoids suppress and can atrophy the adrenal cortex; withdrawal should be progressive, confirming adequate endogenous axis recovery with an ACTH stimulation test before stopping completely."},
    {front:"What is an adrenal incidentaloma, and how common is it?", back:"A nodule greater than 10mm found incidentally on imaging done for another reason; very common and usually asymptomatic."},
    {front:"What is the typical CT and MRI appearance of a benign adrenal adenoma?", back:"CT: low density on the pre-contrast phase with fast contrast washout by the late phase (about 10 minutes). MRI: signal loss on chemical shift imaging (similar to fatty liver), reflecting a lipid-rich \"fatty\" adenoma."},
    {front:"What are the imaging features and typical demographics of adrenal cortical carcinoma (ACC)?", back:"A nodule generally over 4cm; rare, more common in women (often age 40-50), without a clear stepwise progression from a benign adenoma. CT shows a non-homogeneous mass with central necrosis, calcification, irregular/diffuse borders, and high density. About 60% present with hyperadrenalism (excess cortisol, with or without excess androgens), along with stomach ache and back pain."},
    {front:"What is the treatment for ACC?", back:"Adrenalectomy if detected early; mitotane, which is specifically cytotoxic to adrenal tissue, is used for advanced/inoperable disease and requires management of the resulting hypoadrenalism."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"Which finding distinguishes primary from secondary adrenal insufficiency on physical exam?", options:["Hyperpigmentation, present only in primary disease due to elevated ACTH/MSH","Salt craving, present only in secondary disease","Hyponatremia, present only in secondary disease","Weight gain, present only in primary disease"], answer:0, explain:"High ACTH in primary adrenal insufficiency also raises MSH (shared POMC precursor), causing hyperpigmentation — absent in secondary disease, where ACTH is low.", ref:2},
    {q:"What is considered a normal cortisol response on an ACTH stimulation test?", options:["Greater than about 18-20 mcg% (550 nmol/L)","Greater than 5 mcg%","No rise at all is expected","Greater than 100 mcg%"], answer:0, explain:"A post-stimulation cortisol above roughly 18-20 mcg% (550 nmol/L) is considered a normal, intact response.", ref:5},
    {q:"A patient on chronic hydrocortisone replacement is admitted for emergency surgery. How should her glucocorticoid dose be adjusted?", options:["Increased roughly 10-fold to cover major physiologic stress","Kept exactly the same as her home dose","Decreased, since surgery reduces cortisol needs","Stopped entirely until she recovers"], answer:0, explain:"Major stress such as surgery or a medical emergency requires roughly a 10-fold increase in glucocorticoid dosing to mimic the physiologic stress response, versus about 2-3 fold for minor stress like fever.", ref:6},
    {q:"A 4.5cm adrenal incidentaloma on CT shows a non-homogeneous mass with central necrosis, calcification, and irregular borders. What is the most likely diagnosis?", options:["Adrenal cortical carcinoma (ACC)","A benign lipid-rich adenoma","A simple adrenal cyst","Adrenal myelolipoma"], answer:0, explain:"Non-homogeneous density, central necrosis/calcification, irregular borders, and size over 4cm are characteristic of ACC, unlike the low-density, homogeneous, fast-washout appearance of a benign adenoma.", ref:10},
    {q:"What is the specific pharmacologic treatment for adrenal cortical carcinoma, and what does it require monitoring for?", options:["Mitotane, which requires monitoring for and treating the resulting hypoadrenalism","Ketoconazole, which requires monitoring for hepatotoxicity only","Metyrapone, which requires no monitoring","Desmopressin, which requires monitoring for hyponatremia"], answer:0, explain:"Mitotane is specifically cytotoxic to adrenal tissue and is used in ACC, but this same cytotoxicity necessitates monitoring and treating the resulting hypoadrenalism.", ref:11}
  ]
},
{
  id: "endo-adrenal-secreting-pheo",
  name: "Hormone-Secreting Adrenal Tumors & Pheochromocytoma",
  blurb: "Cortisol-, aldosterone-, and catecholamine-secreting adrenal nodules, and the pheochromocytoma workup.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"What hormones can a hormone-secreting adrenal nodule produce, and what does \"SCCS\" refer to?", back:"Cortisol, catecholamines, aldosterone, or androgens. SCCS (subclinical Cushing's syndrome) refers to a nodule with mild, subclinical cortisol excess."},
    {front:"What clinical clues suggest a cortisol-, catecholamine-, or aldosterone-secreting adrenal nodule respectively?", back:"Cortisol: diabetes and drug-resistant hypertension (with leukocytosis also described as a Cushing-related clue). Catecholamines: hypertension with paroxysmal elevations. Aldosterone: hypokalemia and hypernatremia."},
    {front:"Why is every adrenal nodule over 10mm assessed for hormone secretion, even if the patient has no symptoms?", back:"Because hormone-secreting nodules can be subclinical (e.g. SCCS) yet still carry cardiometabolic risk, so biochemical screening is performed regardless of symptoms."},
    {front:"How is a cortisol-secreting adenoma diagnosed?", back:"An overnight (before-sleep) dexamethasone suppression test that fails to lower morning cortisol below about 138 nmol/L, together with a positive urinary or salivary cortisol test."},
    {front:"What are the criteria for definitive (surgical) treatment of an adrenal nodule?", back:"Cushing's syndrome, high suspicion of malignancy, or a nodule over about 6cm (or 4-6cm with malignant imaging features); surgery is laparoscopic unless there is a high malignancy risk."},
    {front:"What special perioperative precautions are needed before adrenal surgery for Cushing's syndrome versus pheochromocytoma?", back:"Cushing's syndrome: cover for loss of endogenous corticosteroid production before and after surgery. Pheochromocytoma: alpha- and beta-blockade beforehand to prevent an acute hypertensive crisis during tumor manipulation."},
    {front:"What is a pheochromocytoma, and what syndrome does it cause?", back:"A rare neuroendocrine tumor that oversecretes catecholamines (adrenaline, noradrenaline, metanephrines), causing a hyperadrenergic syndrome — tachycardia, sweating, anxiety, and palpitations."},
    {front:"What is the approximate \"rule of 10s\" for pheochromocytoma described in this lecture?", back:"About 10% are extra-adrenal (called paraganglioma), 10% are bilateral, 10% are malignant, and 30-40% are associated with genetic syndromes; extra-adrenal tumors (PPGL) arise from autonomic peripheral nervous system ganglia."},
    {front:"How is pheochromocytoma diagnosed?", back:"Clinically (headaches, palpitations, hypertension, sympathetic symptoms); chemically (24-hour urine collection for catecholamines and metanephrines); and with imaging — a vascular, dense tumor similar in appearance to ACC — with functional imaging using somatostatin-based tracers or F-DOPA."},
    {front:"Why is alpha-blockade started before beta-blockade when preparing a pheochromocytoma patient for surgery?", back:"Alpha-blockade first controls blood pressure and allows volume expansion; starting a beta-blocker first could leave alpha-mediated vasoconstriction unopposed and precipitate a hypertensive crisis."},
    {front:"What follow-up is needed after treatment for pheochromocytoma?", back:"Genetic counseling and annual urine testing for catecholamines/metanephrines, since about 10% of cases relapse."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"An adrenal incidentaloma workup reveals hypokalemia and hypernatremia. Which hormone is most likely being oversecreted?", options:["Aldosterone","Cortisol","Catecholamines","Androgens"], answer:0, explain:"Hypokalemia with hypernatremia is the classic biochemical signature of aldosterone excess (primary hyperaldosteronism).", ref:1},
    {q:"How is a cortisol-secreting adrenal adenoma diagnosed?", options:["An overnight dexamethasone suppression test that fails to lower morning cortisol, plus a positive urinary/salivary cortisol test","A single random afternoon cortisol level","24-hour urine metanephrines","An ACTH stimulation test showing a robust rise"], answer:0, explain:"Failure of overnight dexamethasone to suppress morning cortisol, combined with elevated urinary or salivary cortisol, supports autonomous cortisol secretion from the adenoma.", ref:3},
    {q:"Which adrenal nodule characteristic mandates definitive surgical treatment rather than clinical monitoring?", options:["Size over about 6cm, or 4-6cm with malignant imaging features","Any nodule over 1cm regardless of features","A purely cystic appearance","Bilateral nodules of any size"], answer:0, explain:"Definitive surgery is indicated for Cushing's syndrome, high malignancy suspicion, or a nodule over ~6cm (or 4-6cm with malignant features).", ref:4},
    {q:"Before pheochromocytoma surgery, why is alpha-blockade started before beta-blockade?", options:["Starting a beta-blocker first could leave alpha-mediated vasoconstriction unopposed, risking a hypertensive crisis","Beta-blockers are contraindicated in all pheochromocytoma patients","Alpha-blockade has no role in pheochromocytoma management","Beta-blockade must always precede any antihypertensive therapy"], answer:0, explain:"Alpha-blockade first controls blood pressure and permits volume expansion; giving a beta-blocker first risks unopposed alpha-receptor vasoconstriction and a hypertensive crisis.", ref:9},
    {q:"What proportion of pheochromocytomas are extra-adrenal (paraganglioma) by this lecture's rule of 10s, and what is the recommended long-term follow-up?", options:["About 10%; annual urine catecholamine/metanephrine testing given a ~10% relapse rate","About 50%; no follow-up is needed after surgery","About 90%; annual imaging only","About 1%; genetic testing only if symptomatic"], answer:0, explain:"About 10% of pheochromocytomas are extra-adrenal; because roughly 10% relapse, annual urine testing and genetic counseling are recommended.", ref:10}
  ]
},
{
  id: "endo-thyroid-function",
  name: "Thyroid Function Disorders",
  blurb: "Hyperthyroidism vs. thyroiditis vs. Graves', euthyroid sick syndrome, and iodine/amiodarone-induced thyroid dysfunction.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"Why is hyperthyroidism defined primarily by TSH levels rather than T3/T4?", back:"TSH is very sensitive to circulating T3/T4 levels and can fall before T3/T4 become frankly elevated — this early state is called subclinical hyperthyroidism."},
    {front:"What happens to thyroid hormone levels during thyroiditis, and why?", back:"During the inflammatory process, thyroid cells release stored T4, transiently raising blood levels (\"pseudo-hyperthyroidism\"). As these stores are depleted, T4 normalizes and TSH falls further (negative feedback lag), resulting in a later transient hypothyroid phase."},
    {front:"How is thyroiditis distinguished from true hyperthyroidism using serial labs?", back:"Repeating T3/T4 levels after about 2 weeks reveals the dynamic, self-resolving pattern of thyroiditis rather than a sustained hyperthyroid state."},
    {front:"What is Graves' disease, and what is a distinguishing clinical sign?", back:"An autoimmune disease causing diffuse thyroid hyperactivity; a chronic presentation with Graves' ophthalmopathy is a distinguishing sign not seen in other causes of hyperthyroidism."},
    {front:"What does thyroid scintigraphy (technetium mapping) show in a normal gland, thyroiditis, a toxic adenoma, and Graves' disease respectively?", back:"Normal: diffuse \"butterfly\" signal. Thyroiditis: no signal (hormone is only being released from stores, not newly produced/taken up). Toxic adenoma: a very strong focal signal in the adenoma with suppression (no signal) in the rest of the gland, from negative feedback. Graves' disease: a strong, diffuse signal throughout the gland."},
    {front:"What additional tests support a diagnosis of Graves' disease, and what is a limitation of neck ultrasound?", back:"Anti-TSH receptor (anti-TSHr) antibodies support Graves' disease; neck ultrasound cannot reliably differentiate benign from malignant thyroid nodules."},
    {front:"What is the treatment approach for hyperthyroidism by cause?", back:"Symptomatic control: beta-blockers. Thyroiditis: self-limited, managed with NSAIDs and steroids for pain. Graves'/overproduction: methimazole (mercaptizole) or PTU (preferred in pregnancy), radioactive iodine to ablate the gland, or surgical thyroidectomy. Toxic adenoma: surgery or radioactive iodine."},
    {front:"What is the typical remission timeline for Graves' disease with medical treatment?", back:"Most cases achieve remission after 1-1.5 years of treatment."},
    {front:"What is euthyroid sick syndrome, and what is its lab pattern?", back:"During acute illness, inflammatory cytokines reduce TSH and shift T4 metabolism toward reverse T3 (rT3) rather than active T3; labs show low TSH, low T3, and normal T4, with severity correlating directly with the severity of the underlying illness. Treatment is to treat the underlying illness."},
    {front:"What iodine intake threshold is associated with thyroid dysfunction, and what is the Wolff-Chaikoff effect?", back:"Iodine intake above about 150mcg/day can trigger thyroid defense mechanisms. The Wolff-Chaikoff effect: high iodine transiently inhibits thyroid peroxidase (TPO) and the sodium-iodide symporter (NIS) for 7-10 days; if the gland fails to \"escape\" and recover, this can lead to hypothyroidism."},
    {front:"What is the Jod-Basedow effect?", back:"A high iodine load entering the thyroid gland triggers transient hyperthyroidism (the opposite response to the Wolff-Chaikoff effect)."},
    {front:"How does amiodarone affect the thyroid, and what are the two types of amiodarone-induced thyrotoxicosis (AIT)?", back:"Amiodarone has a high iodine content (triggering Wolff-Chaikoff-type effects) plus a direct thyroid-toxic effect. AIT type I: overproduction from an underlying nodular gland, treated with methimazole (mercaptizole). AIT type II: a destructive (acute) thyroiditis, treated with steroids."},
    {front:"How are AIT type I and type II differentiated in practice?", back:"By response to treatment/speed of resolution — if resolution is fast (under about 2-3 weeks), this favors type II (destructive thyroiditis)."},
    {front:"What are the causes of hypothyroidism described in this lecture?", back:"Hashimoto's thyroiditis (autoimmune, T-cell mediated, with lymphocytic infiltration of the gland); iatrogenic (post radioactive iodine or thyroidectomy, drug-induced); and transient (post Wolff-Chaikoff effect, post-thyroiditis, or after stopping a thyrotoxic drug)."},
    {front:"What is the treatment for hypothyroidism, and what should be monitored?", back:"Levothyroxine (synthetic T4) — it has a narrow therapeutic window and blood TSH/T4 levels need to be monitored to adjust dosing (e.g. dose requirements can rise with estrogen-containing medications like birth control pills, which increase binding-globulin levels)."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"A patient has an acute illness with elevated T4 that later normalizes and is followed by a transient period of low T3/T4. What is the most likely diagnosis?", options:["Thyroiditis","Graves' disease","A toxic adenoma","Secondary hyperthyroidism"], answer:0, explain:"Thyroiditis releases stored T4 (transient pseudo-hyperthyroidism), then transitions to a transient hypothyroid phase as TSH lags in recovering — confirmed by repeating T3/T4 after about 2 weeks.", ref:2},
    {q:"Thyroid scintigraphy shows a single very strong focal uptake area with the remainder of the gland showing no signal. What does this represent?", options:["A toxic adenoma, with the rest of the gland suppressed by negative feedback","Graves' disease, with diffuse gland activation","Thyroiditis, with no hormone production","A normal thyroid gland"], answer:0, explain:"A toxic adenoma autonomously overproduces hormone, suppressing TSH and, via negative feedback, silencing uptake in the rest of the normal gland.", ref:4},
    {q:"What is the key difference between the Wolff-Chaikoff and Jod-Basedow effects?", options:["Wolff-Chaikoff is iodine-induced suppression of thyroid hormone production; Jod-Basedow is iodine-induced excess thyroid hormone production","Wolff-Chaikoff only occurs with iodine deficiency; Jod-Basedow only occurs with iodine excess","They are the same phenomenon under different names","Wolff-Chaikoff is permanent; Jod-Basedow always resolves within 24 hours"], answer:0, explain:"The Wolff-Chaikoff effect is a high-iodine-induced, transient inhibition of TPO/NIS (risking hypothyroidism if the gland fails to escape); the Jod-Basedow effect is high iodine triggering transient hyperthyroidism — opposite directions of dysfunction from the same iodine-excess trigger.", ref:9},
    {q:"A patient on amiodarone develops thyrotoxicosis that resolves within 2 weeks of starting steroids. What type of amiodarone-induced thyrotoxicosis (AIT) is this, and what is its mechanism?", options:["AIT type II — a destructive (acute) thyroiditis","AIT type I — overproduction from an underlying nodular gland","Graves' disease unmasked by amiodarone","Wolff-Chaikoff-induced hypothyroidism"], answer:0, explain:"Fast resolution (under about 2-3 weeks) with steroid treatment favors AIT type II, a destructive thyroiditis, as opposed to AIT type I (overproduction), which is treated with methimazole.", ref:12},
    {q:"A woman on stable levothyroxine dosing starts combined oral contraceptives. What is the expected effect on her thyroid hormone requirements?", options:["Her levothyroxine dose requirement will likely increase","Her levothyroxine dose requirement will likely decrease","No change in requirement is expected","She should stop levothyroxine entirely"], answer:0, explain:"Estrogen-containing medications raise thyroid-binding globulin levels, typically increasing the levothyroxine dose needed to maintain the same free hormone level.", ref:14}
  ]
},
{
  id: "endo-thyroid-nodules",
  name: "Thyroid Nodules & Cancer",
  blurb: "Assessing a thyroid nodule, the major thyroid cancer subtypes, their treatment, and follow-up.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"How common are thyroid adenomas/nodules, and at what size can they typically be felt during swallowing?", back:"Very common, mostly benign; nodules over about 2cm can typically be felt during swallowing."},
    {front:"What is the initial assessment algorithm for a thyroid nodule?", back:"Check TSH first. If TSH is low, proceed to thyroid scintigraphy (mapping) and ultrasound to assess risk. Suspicious ultrasound features include a hypoechoic nodule, calcifications, and diffuse/irregular borders."},
    {front:"What is fine-needle aspiration (puncture) of a thyroid nodule used for, and what proportion of cases are malignant?", back:"It is taken for cytology; about 5% of aspirated nodules are malignant, and 10-15% of cases require repeat/second testing."},
    {front:"How common is thyroid cancer overall, and how aggressive is it typically?", back:"Usually non-aggressive; very common, with about 6% of the population found to have small cancerous foci."},
    {front:"List the major histologic types of thyroid cancer, from most common to most aggressive.", back:"Papillary (most common), follicular, Hurthle cell, anaplastic (1-2% of cases, very aggressive), and medullary (a neuroendocrine tumor producing calcitonin)."},
    {front:"What is the general treatment approach for differentiated thyroid cancer?", back:"TSH suppression (since tumor cells remain dependent on TSH-receptor signaling), radioactive iodine, and surgery for larger tumors (over about 1cm); tyrosine kinase inhibitors (TKIs) are reserved for rare aggressive cases."},
    {front:"What are the main complications of thyroid surgery, and how common are they?", back:"About 1% of cases develop hypocalcemia (from parathyroid injury) or recurrent laryngeal nerve injury (vocal cord paralysis)."},
    {front:"What tumor marker is used for thyroid cancer follow-up, and what is the treatment goal?", back:"Thyroglobulin — levels should fall to zero after successful treatment; a rising level suggests recurrence."},
    {front:"What genetic association does medullary thyroid cancer have?", back:"MEN2 mutation (RET proto-oncogene); it is a neuroendocrine tumor that produces calcitonin."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"A thyroid nodule is found on exam. What is the recommended first step in assessment?", options:["Check the TSH level","Immediate fine-needle aspiration regardless of TSH","Immediate surgery","A 24-hour urine metanephrine collection"], answer:0, explain:"TSH is checked first; if low, thyroid scintigraphy and ultrasound follow to further characterize the nodule.", ref:1},
    {q:"Which thyroid cancer subtype is the most aggressive?", options:["Anaplastic","Papillary","Follicular","Medullary"], answer:0, explain:"Anaplastic thyroid cancer (about 1-2% of cases) is by far the most aggressive subtype; papillary is the most common and generally indolent.", ref:4},
    {q:"After thyroidectomy for differentiated thyroid cancer, which tumor marker is followed, and what is the treatment goal for its level?", options:["Thyroglobulin, with a goal of trending to zero","Calcitonin, with a goal of trending to zero","Chromogranin A, with a goal of trending to zero","TSH, with a goal of trending to zero"], answer:0, explain:"Thyroglobulin is the follow-up marker for differentiated (papillary/follicular) thyroid cancer, and should fall to zero after successful treatment.", ref:7},
    {q:"A thyroid cancer is found to produce calcitonin and is associated with a RET mutation. What is this cancer, and what syndrome is it linked to?", options:["Medullary thyroid cancer, linked to MEN2","Papillary thyroid cancer, linked to MEN1","Anaplastic thyroid cancer, linked to MEN4","Follicular thyroid cancer, linked to NF1"], answer:0, explain:"Medullary thyroid cancer is a calcitonin-producing neuroendocrine tumor associated with RET mutations in MEN2 syndrome.", ref:8}
  ]
},
{
  id: "endo-net-syndromes",
  name: "Neuroendocrine Tumor Syndromes & Hypoglycemia",
  blurb: "Carcinoid syndrome, insulinoma, gastrinoma, glucagonoma, VIPoma, and working up hypoglycemia.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"What are neuroendocrine tumors (NETs), and what unique features do they share?", back:"Hormone-secreting tumors originating from hormonal glands (e.g. the pituitary) or from endocrine cells scattered across the GI or respiratory tract (e.g. Langerhans cells); shared features include somatostatin receptor expression and typically slow, progressive growth."},
    {front:"What is carcinoid syndrome, where do these tumors usually arise, and how is it diagnosed?", back:"A syndrome from serotonin-secreting tumors, most often arising in the small intestine or lungs; diagnosed using urinary 5-HIAA levels. Symptoms include facial/truncal flushing, stomach ache, diarrhea, and carcinoid heart disease (right-sided heart valve disease)."},
    {front:"What is an insulinoma, and what does it cause?", back:"An insulin-secreting tumor, causing hypoglycemia."},
    {front:"What is a gastrinoma, and what syndrome does it cause?", back:"A gastrin-secreting tumor causing Zollinger-Ellison syndrome — GI ulcers and diarrhea."},
    {front:"What does a glucagonoma cause?", back:"Diabetes, diarrhea, and a characteristic rash."},
    {front:"What does a VIPoma cause?", back:"Watery diarrhea and fluid loss."},
    {front:"What is Whipple's triad, and what is it used for?", back:"The diagnostic basis for hypoglycemia assessment: low blood glucose (below about 55-70 depending on diabetic status), adrenergic or neuroglycopenic symptoms, and resolution of those symptoms when the glucose level is corrected."},
    {front:"What is \"hypoglycemia unawareness\"?", back:"A rare state of asymptomatic hypoglycemia — dangerous because the usual warning symptoms are absent, making it potentially life-threatening."},
    {front:"What causes endogenous hypoglycemia, and how is it distinguished from exogenous hypoglycemia?", back:"Endogenous causes include insulinoma, beta-cell hyperplasia, sulfonylurea/meglitinide drug use, and autoimmune hypoglycemia. Exogenous hypoglycemia is caused by injected insulin. They are distinguished using C-peptide levels — high C-peptide indicates endogenous insulin production, since injected insulin does not carry C-peptide."},
    {front:"What are insulin-independent causes of hypoglycemia?", back:"IGF-2-secreting tumors, hypoadrenalism, and alcoholism."},
    {front:"What is an insulinoma's cell of origin, associated genetic syndrome, and typical behavior?", back:"Originates from pancreatic beta cells, is mostly benign, and is associated with MEN1 syndrome."},
    {front:"What are the symptoms of insulinoma, and how is it worked up?", back:"Repeated hypoglycemic episodes, with preventive/anticipatory eating (including at night) leading to weight gain. Labs show elevated insulin and C-peptide during a spontaneous or fasting-induced (up to 72-hour fast) hypoglycemic episode; imaging includes MRI, CT, endoscopic ultrasound (EUS), and somatostatin-receptor mapping."},
    {front:"What is the treatment for insulinoma?", back:"Surgery is definitive; nutritional monitoring, diazoxide (an insulin secretion suppressor), and somatostatin analogs are used when surgery is not immediately possible or curative."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"A patient has episodic flushing, diarrhea, and a new right-sided heart valve lesion. Which urine test supports the diagnosis?", options:["5-HIAA (a serotonin metabolite)","24-hour urine free cortisol","24-hour urine catecholamines","Urine calcium/creatinine ratio"], answer:0, explain:"Carcinoid syndrome (serotonin-secreting tumor) is diagnosed using urinary 5-HIAA; the described triad plus carcinoid heart disease (right heart valve involvement) is classic.", ref:1},
    {q:"What are the three components of Whipple's triad, used to confirm true hypoglycemia?", options:["Low blood glucose, symptoms consistent with hypoglycemia, and symptom resolution once glucose is corrected","Low blood glucose, high insulin, and high C-peptide","High blood glucose, polyuria, and polydipsia","Low blood glucose, seizures, and a family history of diabetes"], answer:0, explain:"Whipple's triad requires documented low glucose, compatible symptoms, and resolution of those symptoms with glucose correction.", ref:6},
    {q:"A patient with hypoglycemia has a high insulin level. Which additional test best distinguishes endogenous (e.g. insulinoma) from exogenous (injected) insulin as the cause?", options:["C-peptide level — high favors endogenous, low favors exogenous","Fasting glucagon level","24-hour urine 5-HIAA","Serum calcium level"], answer:0, explain:"Endogenously produced insulin is co-secreted with C-peptide, while injected insulin formulations lack C-peptide — so a high C-peptide points to an endogenous source such as insulinoma.", ref:8},
    {q:"A patient with recurrent hypoglycemia and weight gain (from preventive eating) is found to have elevated insulin and C-peptide during a 72-hour fast. What tumor, and with which syndrome is it associated?", options:["Insulinoma; MEN1","Gastrinoma; MEN2","Glucagonoma; VHL","VIPoma; NF1"], answer:0, explain:"This is the classic presentation and workup for insulinoma, a pancreatic beta-cell tumor associated with MEN1 syndrome.", ref:10},
    {q:"A patient has new diabetes, diarrhea, and a characteristic rash. Which NET is most likely?", options:["Glucagonoma","Insulinoma","Gastrinoma","Carcinoid tumor"], answer:0, explain:"Glucagonoma classically causes diabetes, diarrhea, and a characteristic rash (necrolytic migratory erythema).", ref:4}
  ]
},
{
  id: "endo-net-workup-men",
  name: "NET Workup, Treatment & MEN Syndromes",
  blurb: "Imaging and pathology for neuroendocrine tumors, systemic treatment options, and the inherited MEN syndromes.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"What lab test is used to screen for carcinoid syndrome, and what marker is used more broadly (but non-specifically) for NETs?", back:"Urinary 5-HIAA for carcinoid syndrome; chromogranin A is a non-specific NET marker that can also be elevated by proton pump inhibitor (PPI) use, which should be considered when interpreting an elevated result."},
    {front:"What imaging modalities are used for NETs, and which is considered the gold standard?", back:"CT, MRI, and endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) are used; gallium-68 DOTATATE PET-CT (a somatostatin-receptor-targeted PET tracer) is considered the gold standard."},
    {front:"What pathology stains are used to confirm a NET diagnosis, and what does Ki-67 staining indicate?", back:"Chromogranin and synaptophysin confirm neuroendocrine differentiation; Ki-67 staining reflects the proliferation rate, informing tumor grade."},
    {front:"What is the definitive treatment for NETs, and what medical options exist for metastatic disease?", back:"Surgery is definitive when feasible. For metastatic disease: somatostatin analogs (octreotide, lanreotide, pasireotide — given by injection roughly every 4 weeks) for symptomatic hormone-secretion control, and biologic agents (everolimus, sunitinib) for tumor control."},
    {front:"What is PRRT, and what is its major side effect?", back:"Peptide receptor radionuclide therapy — targeted irradiation using a radiolabeled somatostatin analog; its major side effect is bone marrow suppression."},
    {front:"What liver-directed therapies are used for metastatic NET disease in the liver?", back:"Radioablation and chemoembolization, targeted at hepatic metastases."},
    {front:"What is the general genetic pattern of MEN syndromes, and what does Von Hippel-Lindau (VHL) syndrome cause?", back:"MEN syndromes are caused by autosomal dominant mutations. VHL syndrome (VHL gene mutation) causes multiple hemangiomas/angiomas, renal cell carcinoma, pheochromocytoma, and pancreatic NETs."},
    {front:"What does NF1 (neurofibromatosis type 1) cause?", back:"Café-au-lait spots, neurofibromas, CNS tumors, pheochromocytoma, and NETs."},
    {front:"What is MEN1, and what tumors does it involve?", back:"A tumor-suppressor-gene mutation (following a two-hit model) causing multiple pituitary, parathyroid, and pancreatic NETs."},
    {front:"What are MEN2 and MEN3, and how do their features differ?", back:"Both are caused by RET mutations, causing medullary thyroid NETs and pheochromocytoma. MEN2 additionally involves parathyroid and skin tumors; MEN3 is more aggressive and involves mucosal neuromas. Preventive thyroidectomy is recommended in these syndromes."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"Which imaging study is considered the gold standard for localizing a neuroendocrine tumor?", options:["Gallium-68 DOTATATE PET-CT","Non-contrast CT alone","Technetium bone scan","Carotid ultrasound"], answer:0, explain:"Somatostatin-receptor-targeted PET-CT using gallium-68 DOTATATE is the gold standard for NET imaging, reflecting the tumors' characteristic somatostatin receptor expression.", ref:1},
    {q:"A patient on long-term PPI therapy has a mildly elevated chromogranin A. What is the significance of this finding?", options:["Chromogranin A is non-specific and can be elevated by PPI use, so this alone does not confirm a NET","It is diagnostic of carcinoid syndrome","It confirms an insulinoma","It rules out any neuroendocrine tumor"], answer:0, explain:"Chromogranin A is a non-specific NET marker that can be falsely elevated by PPI use, so an elevated level must be interpreted in that context.", ref:0},
    {q:"What does Ki-67 staining indicate on NET pathology?", options:["The tumor's proliferation rate, informing grade","The tumor's hormone of secretion","Whether the tumor is somatostatin-receptor positive","Whether the tumor has metastasized"], answer:0, explain:"Ki-67 is a proliferation marker used to grade NETs; higher Ki-67 indicates a more proliferative, higher-grade tumor.", ref:2},
    {q:"A patient has multiple pituitary, parathyroid, and pancreatic neuroendocrine tumors. Which MEN syndrome is this, and what is the underlying genetic mechanism?", options:["MEN1 — a tumor-suppressor-gene mutation (two-hit model)","MEN2 — a RET proto-oncogene mutation","VHL syndrome — a VHL gene mutation","NF1 — a neurofibromin gene mutation"], answer:0, explain:"MEN1 involves pituitary, parathyroid, and pancreatic NETs, caused by a tumor-suppressor-gene mutation following a two-hit mechanism.", ref:8},
    {q:"A patient with medullary thyroid cancer and pheochromocytoma is found to have a RET mutation. Which MEN syndromes are consistent with this, and what preventive procedure is recommended?", options:["MEN2/MEN3; preventive thyroidectomy","MEN1; preventive parathyroidectomy","VHL syndrome; preventive nephrectomy","NF1; preventive adrenalectomy"], answer:0, explain:"Medullary thyroid cancer plus pheochromocytoma with a RET mutation is characteristic of MEN2/MEN3, for which preventive thyroidectomy is recommended given the near-universal risk of medullary thyroid cancer.", ref:9}
  ]
},
{
  id: "endo-calcium-hypercalcemia",
  name: "Calcium-Phosphate Homeostasis & Hypercalcemia",
  blurb: "PTH, vitamin D, and phosphate physiology, and the workup and treatment of PTH-dependent vs. PTH-independent hypercalcemia.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"What is CaSR, and what happens when calcium levels are low?", back:"The calcium-sensing receptor, found on parathyroid and renal cells; low calcium levels are sensed by CaSR and induce PTH secretion."},
    {front:"What are the three main actions of PTH?", back:"It enhances renal calcium-phosphate exchange (retaining calcium, excreting phosphate), increases bone osteoclast activity (releasing calcium from bone), and enhances vitamin D production (which in turn increases intestinal calcium absorption)."},
    {front:"How does phosphate feed back on PTH and vitamin D?", back:"High blood phosphate enhances both PTH and FGF23 secretion; FGF23 induces renal phosphate excretion and lowers (active) vitamin D levels."},
    {front:"What is the pathway of vitamin D activation?", back:"D3 is produced in the skin from 7-dehydrocholesterol using sunlight; it is converted in the liver to inactive 25-hydroxy vitamin D, then fully activated in the kidneys to 1,25-dihydroxy vitamin D."},
    {front:"What are the diagnostic thresholds for hypercalcemia and severe hypercalcemia?", back:"Hypercalcemia: calcium above 10.4. Severe hypercalcemia: above 14."},
    {front:"What are the symptoms of hypercalcemia?", back:"Polyuria and polydipsia (from a nephrogenic diabetes-insipidus-like effect), renal colic, GI symptoms, muscle weakness and aches, attention deficits, and hypertension."},
    {front:"How is hypercalcemia initially evaluated?", back:"PTH levels differentiate PTH-dependent (hyperactive parathyroid) from PTH-independent causes; additional labs include (inactive) vitamin D levels and a urine collection for calcium and creatinine."},
    {front:"What are the causes of PTH-dependent hypercalcemia?", back:"Primary hyperparathyroidism, and conditions of CaSR hypersensitivity such as lithium use or familial hypocalciuric hypercalcemia (FHH, an autosomal dominant CaSR inactivating mutation)."},
    {front:"What are the etiology, complications, and treatment of primary hyperparathyroidism?", back:"More common in women. Etiology: isolated or multiple adenomas (benign), 4-gland hyperplasia (as in MEN syndromes), or rarely carcinoma. Complications: osteopenia/osteoporosis (from enhanced osteoclast activity) and renal colic (assessed with kidney ultrasound and bone density testing). Treatment: surgical adenoma removal (preferred in young, symptomatic patients), localized with ultrasound, technetium scintigraphy, or CT; non-surgical options include anti-osteoclast agents (bisphosphonates, denosumab) and cinacalcet (which reduces CaSR sensitivity)."},
    {front:"What are the causes of PTH-independent hypercalcemia?", back:"Malignancy (often via PTHrP, a PTH-homologous protein secreted by tumors), vitamin D toxicity, granulomatous disease, hyperthyroidism, NETs, and drug-induced causes (e.g. thiazides)."},
    {front:"What is localized osteolytic hypercalcemia?", back:"Severe hypercalcemia from direct, localized bone lysis, caused by multiple myeloma or bone metastases."},
    {front:"What is the treatment for significant hypercalcemia?", back:"Hydration, loop diuretics, anti-osteoclast agents, calcitonin, steroids (particularly for granulomatous-disease-related hypercalcemia), and dialysis in severe/refractory cases."},
    {front:"What is secondary hyperparathyroidism?", back:"A compensatory rise in PTH due to chronic hypocalcemia — from vitamin D deficiency, chronic kidney disease, or certain drugs."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"What is the effect of PTH on bone, kidney, and vitamin D metabolism?", options:["Increases bone osteoclast activity, enhances renal calcium-phosphate exchange, and increases vitamin D production","Decreases bone osteoclast activity, decreases renal calcium reabsorption, and decreases vitamin D production","Increases bone osteoblast activity only, with no renal or vitamin D effect","Has no effect on bone but only affects vitamin D metabolism"], answer:0, explain:"PTH raises serum calcium via three coordinated actions: increased bone osteoclast activity, enhanced renal calcium retention/phosphate excretion, and increased active vitamin D production.", ref:1},
    {q:"A patient has hypercalcemia with an elevated PTH. Ultrasound shows a single parathyroid adenoma. What is the preferred treatment in a young, symptomatic patient?", options:["Surgical removal of the adenoma","Lifelong cinacalcet only","Denosumab only, with no surgery considered","Observation with no treatment"], answer:0, explain:"Surgical adenoma removal is preferred in young, symptomatic patients with primary hyperparathyroidism; cinacalcet and anti-osteoclast agents are non-surgical alternatives for those who are not surgical candidates.", ref:8},
    {q:"A patient with a known malignancy develops hypercalcemia with a low/suppressed PTH. What is the most likely mediator?", options:["PTHrP, a PTH-homologous protein secreted by the tumor","Excess PTH secretion from a parathyroid adenoma","FGF23 excess","CaSR hypersensitivity from lithium use"], answer:0, explain:"Malignancy-associated hypercalcemia is most often mediated by PTHrP, which mimics PTH's effects on bone and kidney while suppressing native PTH via negative feedback on serum calcium.", ref:9},
    {q:"Which of the following is a treatment for severe, symptomatic hypercalcemia?", options:["Hydration, loop diuretics, and anti-osteoclast agents","Fluid restriction and desmopressin","High-dose vitamin D supplementation","Insulin and dextrose infusion"], answer:0, explain:"Hydration, loop diuretics, anti-osteoclast agents (e.g. bisphosphonates), calcitonin, steroids (in granulomatous disease), and dialysis in severe cases are used for hypercalcemia — the opposite approach to hyponatremia/SIADH management.", ref:11},
    {q:"A patient with chronic kidney disease develops a persistently elevated PTH despite low-normal calcium. What is this called?", options:["Secondary hyperparathyroidism","Primary hyperparathyroidism","Tertiary hypoparathyroidism","Pseudohypoparathyroidism"], answer:0, explain:"Secondary hyperparathyroidism is a compensatory PTH rise driven by chronic hypocalcemia, commonly from CKD or vitamin D deficiency.", ref:12}
  ]
},
{
  id: "endo-hypocalcemia",
  name: "Hypocalcemia & Hypoparathyroidism",
  blurb: "Correcting calcium for albumin and pH, bedside signs of tetany, and the genetic and acquired causes of hypocalcemia.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"How should measured calcium be corrected for albumin and pH?", back:"For every 1-unit decrease in albumin, add about 0.8 to the measured calcium level. Acidic pH raises the physiologically active (ionized) calcium, while alkalotic (basic) pH lowers it."},
    {front:"What are the symptoms and signs of hypocalcemia, from mild to severe?", back:"Perioral paresthesias and muscle twitching, hypotension, and arrhythmias; severe cases can show a parkinsonian syndrome, papilledema, and cataracts."},
    {front:"What are the key bedside diagnostic signs of hypocalcemia, and what ECG finding supports it?", back:"Trousseau's sign (inflating a blood pressure cuff causes carpal muscle spasm), Chvostek's sign (tapping over the facial nerve near the zygomatic arch causes facial/jaw twitching), and a prolonged QT interval on ECG."},
    {front:"What are the acquired causes of hypoparathyroidism?", back:"Surgical (post-parathyroidectomy, or as a side effect of thyroidectomy), radioactive iodine treatment, infiltrative disease (granulomatous disease, hemochromatosis), hypomagnesemia, and CaSR autoantibodies (autoimmune)."},
    {front:"What is FIH (familial isolated hypoparathyroidism), and what genes are implicated?", back:"A congenital form of hypoparathyroidism caused by mutations in PTH itself, transcription factors involved in parathyroid development, or (most commonly) the CaSR gene."},
    {front:"What is ADHH, and what is its mechanism?", back:"Autosomal dominant hypocalcemia with hypercalciuria — caused by an overactivating (gain-of-function) CaSR mutation, leading to chronic calciuria and low calcium."},
    {front:"What is APECED syndrome?", back:"An autosomal recessive mutation in the AIRE gene, causing a triad of candidiasis, hypoparathyroidism, and Addison's disease."},
    {front:"What is DiGeorge syndrome, and what does it cause?", back:"An autosomal dominant syndrome from failure of pharyngeal pouches 3-6 to develop, causing congenital heart defects, thymic hypoplasia (immunodeficiency), cleft lip, and hypoparathyroidism."},
    {front:"What is pseudohypoparathyroidism, and how does genetic imprinting affect its presentation?", back:"A PTH receptor mutation that can affect the kidney, the bones, or both. Due to genetic imprinting, the paternal allele is normally silenced in the kidney — so a maternally inherited mutation affects both kidney and bone, while a paternally inherited mutation causes only the bone phenotype (Albright hereditary osteodystrophy, AHO)."},
    {front:"What is hungry bone syndrome?", back:"Massive, rapid calcium uptake into bone after parathyroidectomy or treatment of thyrotoxicosis, causing significant hypocalcemia."},
    {front:"What are the symptoms of vitamin D deficiency, and what are its causes?", back:"Muscle ache and weakness, general weariness, and osteomalacia; causes include lack of sunlight exposure, enzymatic disruption (anti-epileptic drugs disrupting the 25-hydroxylation step, or kidney disease/genetic mutations affecting alpha-hydroxylase), and vitamin D-dependent rickets type 2, where vitamin D fails to act on intestinal absorption despite adequate levels."},
    {front:"What is the treatment for hypocalcemia, acute vs. chronic?", back:"Acute: IV calcium gluconate. Chronic: oral calcium plus vitamin D."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"Inflating a blood pressure cuff on a hypocalcemic patient's arm produces carpal spasm. What is this sign called?", options:["Trousseau's sign","Chvostek's sign","Whipple's triad","CaSR sign"], answer:0, explain:"Trousseau's sign — carpal spasm induced by BP cuff inflation (ischemia unmasking neuromuscular irritability) — is a classic bedside sign of hypocalcemia.", ref:2},
    {q:"A patient has a maternally inherited PTH receptor mutation. Which tissues are affected, and why?", options:["Both kidney and bone, because the paternal allele is normally silenced (imprinted) in the kidney","Only the bone, because the maternal allele is always silenced","Only the kidney, because the paternal allele is always active","Neither tissue, because maternal mutations are never expressed"], answer:0, explain:"Because the paternal PTH-receptor allele is imprinted (silenced) in the kidney, a maternally inherited mutation affects both kidney and bone, while a paternal mutation causes only the bone (AHO) phenotype.", ref:8},
    {q:"A child has congenital heart defects, thymic hypoplasia, cleft lip, and hypoparathyroidism from failure of the 3rd-6th pharyngeal pouches to develop. What is this syndrome?", options:["DiGeorge syndrome","APECED syndrome","ADHH","Familial isolated hypoparathyroidism (FIH)"], answer:0, explain:"DiGeorge syndrome results from failed development of the 3rd-6th pharyngeal pouches, causing cardiac defects, thymic hypoplasia, cleft lip, and hypoparathyroidism.", ref:7},
    {q:"A patient develops severe hypocalcemia in the days after parathyroidectomy for longstanding severe hyperparathyroidism. What is this phenomenon called?", options:["Hungry bone syndrome","Pseudohypoparathyroidism","ADHH","Vitamin D-dependent rickets type 2"], answer:0, explain:"Hungry bone syndrome is rapid, massive calcium uptake into bone following parathyroidectomy (or treatment of thyrotoxicosis), causing pronounced hypocalcemia.", ref:9},
    {q:"What is the appropriate treatment for acute, symptomatic hypocalcemia versus chronic hypocalcemia?", options:["Acute: IV calcium gluconate. Chronic: oral calcium plus vitamin D","Acute: oral calcium only. Chronic: IV calcium gluconate","Both are treated with IV calcium gluconate only","Both are treated with cinacalcet"], answer:0, explain:"Acute, symptomatic hypocalcemia is treated with IV calcium gluconate; chronic hypocalcemia is managed with oral calcium and vitamin D.", ref:11}
  ]
},
{
  id: "endo-osteoporosis",
  name: "Osteoporosis",
  blurb: "DEXA scoring, bone remodeling physiology, fracture risk stratification (FRAX), and the anti-remodeling/osteoanabolic drug classes.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"What does DEXA measure, and across which bone types?", back:"Bone mineral density, across trabecular bone (e.g. spine), mixed cortical/trabecular bone (e.g. the hip/femoral neck), and cortical bone (e.g. the radius)."},
    {front:"What are the T-score thresholds for normal, osteoporosis, and severe osteoporosis?", back:"Normal: above -1. Osteoporosis: below -1. Severe osteoporosis: below -2.5."},
    {front:"Who should be screened for osteoporosis with DEXA?", back:"Women over 65, men over 70, and younger individuals with risk factors (e.g. early menopause, prior fracture history)."},
    {front:"What is the BMU, and what goes wrong with it in osteoporosis?", back:"The basic multicellular unit — a coordinated region of osteoclast and osteoblast activity responsible for normal bone remodeling. In osteoporosis, this remodeling process is disrupted, preventing effective bone renewal."},
    {front:"When does bone mass peak, and what factors affect its subsequent decline?", back:"Bone mass peaks around age 30-35, then gradually declines, affected by genetics, diet, physical activity, smoking, and comorbidities; trabecular bone is affected first."},
    {front:"What are the two main bone turnover markers, and what do they reflect?", back:"CTX reflects osteoclast (bone resorption) activity; P1NP reflects osteoblast (bone formation) activity."},
    {front:"What is the most significant osteoporotic fracture, and what is its outcome?", back:"Femoral neck fracture — the main osteoporotic complication, with a mortality rate over 20% and prolonged rehabilitation with long-term functional effects."},
    {front:"What are the consequences of a vertebral fracture, and when should screening for it be considered?", back:"Pain, height loss, and kyphosis. Screening is recommended in older age, with rapid height loss, or with chronic prednisone use (over 3 months)."},
    {front:"What is FRAX, and when is treatment recommended based on it?", back:"A 10-year fracture risk calculator incorporating DEXA results and clinical risk factors; treatment is recommended when the major fracture risk is over 20% or the hip (femoral neck) fracture risk is over 3%."},
    {front:"What is the recommended vitamin D and calcium intake for osteoporosis treatment/prevention?", back:"A vitamin D level around 75 nmol/L (via 1,000-2,000 units/day), plus a high-calcium diet."},
    {front:"What is raloxifene, and in whom is it preferred?", back:"A selective estrogen receptor modulator (SERM) that reduces vertebral (but not femoral neck) fracture risk and also reduces breast cancer risk; preferred in women under 65 with a low femoral fracture and low thromboembolic risk."},
    {front:"How do bisphosphonates work, and what are the oral versus IV options?", back:"They act as a calcium pyrophosphate mimetic, destroying osteoclasts on contact with a long-term effect. Oral options: risedronate, alendronate. IV: zoledronate — used for high femoral fracture risk, given once yearly for about 6 years."},
    {front:"How does denosumab work, and what is a key risk of stopping it?", back:"A RANKL inhibitor (a synthetic OPG-like effect) that prevents osteoclast activity; stopping denosumab can cause a rapid rebound in osteoclast activity and fracture risk. It is given subcutaneously every 6 months and recommended for very-high-risk patients."},
    {front:"What are the two osteoanabolic agents, and what must follow their use?", back:"Teriparatide (pulsatile PTH, given daily for up to 2 years, with an associated osteosarcoma risk) and romosozumab (a sclerostin inhibitor that both inhibits osteoclasts and activates osteoblasts, with a cardiovascular event risk). Both require a subsequent anti-remodeling (anti-resorptive) agent to maintain the gained bone density."},
    {front:"How is osteoporosis treatment matched to risk level?", back:"Low-to-intermediate risk: consider hormone replacement therapy or a SERM (raloxifene). High risk: oral bisphosphonates or denosumab. Very high risk (T-score below -3): combined anabolic plus anti-remodeling treatment."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"Which bone is typically affected earliest in osteoporosis, and why?", options:["Trabecular bone, because it has a higher surface-area-to-volume ratio and turns over faster","Cortical bone, because it is denser","Both are affected equally at the same rate","Neither type is preferentially affected"], answer:0, explain:"Trabecular bone (e.g. spine) is affected earliest in osteoporosis, reflected in DEXA screening of the spine.", ref:4},
    {q:"A patient's FRAX 10-year major fracture risk is 25%. What does this indicate?", options:["Treatment is recommended, since this exceeds the 20% threshold","No treatment is needed, since this is below the treatment threshold","This score only matters if femoral neck risk is also above 50%","FRAX cannot be used to guide treatment decisions"], answer:0, explain:"Osteoporosis treatment is recommended when FRAX major fracture risk exceeds 20% (or hip fracture risk exceeds 3%).", ref:8},
    {q:"A patient on denosumab wants to stop the medication. What is the key risk of doing so without a follow-up plan?", options:["A rapid rebound increase in osteoclast activity and fracture risk","Permanent, irreversible osteosarcoma risk","Immediate hungry bone syndrome","No risk — denosumab can be stopped at any time without consequence"], answer:0, explain:"Stopping denosumab removes RANKL inhibition abruptly, causing a rebound surge in osteoclast activity and an increased fracture risk if not managed with a transition plan.", ref:12},
    {q:"Which osteoporosis drug carries an osteosarcoma risk and is limited to about 2 years of use?", options:["Teriparatide","Denosumab","Raloxifene","Alendronate"], answer:0, explain:"Teriparatide (pulsatile PTH) is an osteoanabolic agent given daily for up to about 2 years, with an associated osteosarcoma risk; it requires a follow-up anti-remodeling agent.", ref:13},
    {q:"Which SERM reduces vertebral fracture risk and breast cancer risk, but not femoral neck fracture risk?", options:["Raloxifene","Teriparatide","Denosumab","Zoledronate"], answer:0, explain:"Raloxifene reduces vertebral fracture and breast cancer risk without a proven femoral-neck fracture benefit, and is preferred in women under 65 with low femoral/thromboembolic risk.", ref:10}
  ]
},
{
  id: "endo-t2dm-diagnosis-complications",
  name: "Type 2 Diabetes: Diagnosis & Complications",
  blurb: "Screening cutoffs, diagnostic criteria, and the acute and chronic (macro/microvascular) complications of T2DM.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"What is the core pathophysiology of type 2 diabetes, and how does insulin secretion change over time?", back:"Insulin resistance is the core defect; insulin levels are initially high to compensate, but secretion decreases as the disease progresses (beta-cell exhaustion)."},
    {front:"What is the typical lab pattern (glucose, insulin, glucagon) in an established T2DM patient?", back:"Glucose levels are high and remain elevated; insulin remains relatively low (having declined from earlier compensatory highs); glucagon remains elevated."},
    {front:"Which populations should be screened for type 2 diabetes?", back:"Adults over 35, those with a history of gestational diabetes, HIV-positive patients, those with prediabetes, and overweight individuals."},
    {front:"What are the screening/diagnostic cutoffs for fasting glucose, the 2-hour post-75g oral glucose tolerance test, and HbA1c?", back:"Fasting glucose: normal under 100, prediabetes 100-125. 2-hour OGTT: normal under 140, prediabetes in the 140s (with diabetes at higher levels). HbA1c: normal under 5.7%, prediabetes 5.7-6.4%. HbA1c should correlate closely with glucose levels — a mismatch should prompt consideration of a lab/technical error."},
    {front:"What are the diagnostic criteria for type 2 diabetes?", back:"Diabetic criteria met on two separate tests, OR a single test with glucose over 200 accompanied by hyperglycemic symptoms."},
    {front:"How is hypoglycemia severity graded?", back:"Mild: glucose in the 54-70 range. Intermediate: below 54. Severe: defined clinically, by the patient being unable to self-treat/self-sustain."},
    {front:"What is DKA, in which diabetes type is it more common, and what are common precipitants?", back:"Diabetic ketoacidosis — a hyperglycemic, ketotic, acidotic state — more common in type 1 diabetes; precipitated by events such as MI, stroke, PE, or infection."},
    {front:"What is the treatment approach for DKA?", back:"Fluids (1-2L of saline in the first hour), correcting sodium if needed, insulin (aiming to keep glucose above 250 while treating the acidosis, not dropping it too fast), and monitoring/treating potassium (aiming to keep it under 5.5, since insulin will drive potassium intracellularly)."},
    {front:"What is HHS, how does it differ from DKA, and how is it treated?", back:"Hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state — a non-ketotic hyperglycemic emergency, more common in type 2 diabetes. Compared to DKA, HHS presents with higher glucose, higher sodium, and higher osmolarity. Treatment: fluids and insulin (aiming to keep glucose in the 250-300 range), plus potassium management."},
    {front:"What is the formula for corrected sodium in hyperglycemia?", back:"Corrected sodium = measured sodium + 1.6 × (glucose − 100) / 100 — accounting for the dilutional effect of hyperglycemia on sodium."},
    {front:"What are the macrovascular complications of T2DM, and how are they treated?", back:"Ischemic heart disease, TIA/CVA (the most common), and peripheral arterial disease (with a high amputation risk). Treatment: glycemic, lipid, and blood pressure control, plus GLP-1 agonists and SGLT2 inhibitors."},
    {front:"What is diabetic retinopathy, and how is it monitored and treated?", back:"Microaneurysms progressing to non-proliferative or proliferative retinopathy; monitored with yearly ophthalmologic follow-up. Treatment: photocoagulation, anti-VEGF agents, or vitrectomy."},
    {front:"What is diabetic neuropathy, how is it tested, and what does autonomic neuropathy cause?", back:"A \"socks and gloves\" (distal, symmetric) sensory loss pattern, tested with monofilament examination. Autonomic neuropathy causes orthostatic hypotension, silent MI, and GI dysmotility."},
    {front:"What is diabetic nephropathy, and how does GFR change over the disease course?", back:"Early diabetic kidney disease shows an increase in GFR (hyperfiltration), which later decreases as albuminuria (progressing to nephrotic-range proteinuria) develops, leading to CKD, end-stage kidney disease, and high cardiovascular risk. Treatment: ACE inhibitors/ARBs, SGLT2 inhibitors, and GLP-1 agonists."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"A patient has a single glucose reading of 230 with polyuria and polydipsia. Does this meet diagnostic criteria for diabetes?", options:["Yes — a single test with glucose over 200 plus hyperglycemic symptoms is diagnostic","No — two separate abnormal tests are always required regardless of symptoms","No — only an HbA1c can diagnose diabetes","Yes, but only if confirmed by a repeat test on a different day"], answer:0, explain:"Diabetes can be diagnosed either by meeting diabetic criteria on two separate tests, or by a single glucose over 200 accompanied by hyperglycemic symptoms.", ref:4},
    {q:"A patient presents with a hyperglycemic emergency showing very high glucose, high sodium, and high serum osmolarity, without significant ketosis. What is this, and in which diabetes type is it more common?", options:["Hyperosmolar hyperglycemic state (HHS); more common in type 2 diabetes","Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA); more common in type 1 diabetes","Euglycemic DKA; more common with SGLT2 inhibitor use","Lactic acidosis; more common with metformin use"], answer:0, explain:"HHS is a non-ketotic hyperglycemic emergency with higher glucose, sodium, and osmolarity than DKA, and is more common in type 2 diabetes.", ref:8},
    {q:"A patient with DKA has a measured sodium of 130 and a glucose of 500. Using the correction formula, is the true sodium concentration higher or lower than the measured value?", options:["Higher — hyperglycemia dilutes measured sodium, so the corrected value is higher","Lower — hyperglycemia concentrates measured sodium, so the corrected value is lower","The same — glucose does not affect sodium measurement","Cannot be determined without potassium levels"], answer:0, explain:"Hyperglycemia draws water into the vascular space, diluting measured sodium; the correction formula (+1.6 × (glucose−100)/100) raises the reported value to reflect the true total body sodium status.", ref:9},
    {q:"How often should a patient with type 2 diabetes have an ophthalmologic exam to screen for retinopathy?", options:["Yearly","Every 5 years","Only if visual symptoms develop","Every 3 months"], answer:0, explain:"Yearly ophthalmologic follow-up is recommended to detect diabetic retinopathy, since microaneurysms can progress silently to proliferative disease.", ref:11},
    {q:"A patient with long-standing T2DM initially had an elevated GFR, which has since declined alongside new albuminuria. What does this represent?", options:["The expected trajectory of diabetic nephropathy — early hyperfiltration followed by declining GFR as albuminuria develops","A sign that the patient never had diabetic kidney disease","An indication to stop all diabetes medications immediately","A sign of acute kidney injury unrelated to diabetes"], answer:0, explain:"Diabetic nephropathy classically shows an early GFR increase (hyperfiltration), followed by a decline as albuminuria/proteinuria develops, progressing toward CKD/ESKD.", ref:13}
  ]
},
{
  id: "endo-t2dm-treatment",
  name: "Type 2 Diabetes: Treatment & Other Diabetes Types",
  blurb: "The oral/injectable drug classes for T2DM, insulin formulations, inpatient management, and LADA/MODY.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"What are the general glycemic treatment targets for type 2 diabetes?", back:"HbA1c under 7% (under 6.5% if achievable safely) and fasting glucose 80-130, alongside dietary monitoring and physical activity."},
    {front:"What is metformin's mechanism, expected HbA1c effect, and key adverse effects?", back:"Reduces hepatic gluconeogenesis and improves insulin sensitivity, typically lowering HbA1c by more than 1%. Adverse effects: GI symptoms, low vitamin B12 (mitigated by taking it with meals), and a risk of lactic acidosis in chronic kidney disease."},
    {front:"How do sulfonylureas work, and what are their main risks? What is a related short-acting alternative?", back:"They block pancreatic potassium channels, increasing insulin secretion; risks include hypoglycemia and weight gain. Meglitinides are short-acting potassium-channel blockers, used as add-on coverage when other agents don't adequately control glucose."},
    {front:"How does acarbose work, and what limits its use?", back:"It mimics carbohydrates to competitively reduce total carbohydrate absorption; it is less commonly used because of GI side effects (stomach aches, diarrhea)."},
    {front:"How do TZDs (thiazolidinediones) work, and what are their main risks?", back:"They activate PPAR-gamma, causing fat cell proliferation with improved insulin sensitivity; risks include heart failure and peripheral edema."},
    {front:"What is the mechanism of DPP-4 inhibitors, and what are two examples?", back:"They have an effect similar to GLP-1 agonists (by preventing breakdown of endogenous GLP-1); examples include sitagliptin (Januvia) and linagliptin (Trajenta)."},
    {front:"How do SGLT2 inhibitors work, and what are their main risks?", back:"They decrease renal glucose reabsorption; their effect on HbA1c is relatively modest, but they carry risks of genital fungal infection, hypotension, and DKA (even with only modestly elevated glucose) during acute illness."},
    {front:"How do GLP-1 agonists work, and what are their benefits and adverse effects?", back:"They increase insulin secretion, reduce glucagon, slow gastric emptying, and enhance satiety. They are very effective at lowering HbA1c and carry a low cardiovascular risk, but can cause GI adverse effects."},
    {front:"What are the different insulin formulations by onset/duration, and their key features?", back:"Rapid-acting: fast peak (15-20 minutes), taken before meals. Regular: an older, slower formulation. NPH: intermediate-acting, given twice daily, lasting 14-16 hours with a peak at 3-4 hours. Long-acting: lasts about 24 hours. Very-long-acting: lasts 30-40 hours."},
    {front:"What is the typical stepwise treatment approach for type 2 diabetes?", back:"1st line: metformin plus lifestyle changes. An SGLT2 inhibitor or GLP-1 agonist is usually added for patients with coronary/peripheral artery disease, heart failure, chronic kidney disease, or obesity."},
    {front:"If a patient's hyperglycemia fails to improve despite weight loss, what should be reconsidered?", back:"That this may not be typical T2DM — consider type 1 diabetes, pancreatic cancer, pheochromocytoma, hyperthyroidism, a neuroendocrine tumor, cystic fibrosis, Cushing syndrome, acromegaly, or steroid/statin use as an alternative or contributing cause."},
    {front:"What is LADA, and with what is it associated?", back:"Latent autoimmune diabetes in adults — type 1 diabetes with a delayed presentation (around age 35), associated with obesity and positive autoimmune serology (anti-GAD antibodies)."},
    {front:"What is MODY, and how does it typically behave?", back:"Maturity-onset diabetes of the young — caused by autosomal dominant mutations (most commonly HNF1A or glucokinase) causing beta-cell dysfunction with reduced glucose sensing; it is non-progressive and does not cause hyperglycemic emergencies."},
    {front:"What defines inpatient hyperglycemia, what is the target range, and what is the preferred treatment?", back:"Glucose over 140 in a diabetic inpatient, often triggered by acute stress; the target range is 140-180. Insulin is preferred over oral agents, given as a basal-bolus regimen combining basal insulin, nutritional (pre-meal) insulin, and correctional insulin for hyperglycemic excursions."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"Which oral diabetes medication carries a risk of lactic acidosis in patients with chronic kidney disease?", options:["Metformin","A sulfonylurea","A DPP-4 inhibitor","Acarbose"], answer:0, explain:"Metformin carries a lactic acidosis risk in CKD, in addition to its more common GI side effects and B12 deficiency risk.", ref:1},
    {q:"Which diabetes drug class is associated with both strong HbA1c reduction and low cardiovascular risk, but can cause GI side effects?", options:["GLP-1 agonists","Sulfonylureas","TZDs","Acarbose"], answer:0, explain:"GLP-1 agonists provide strong glycemic control with a favorable cardiovascular profile, though GI adverse effects are common.", ref:6},
    {q:"Which insulin formulation is given twice daily, lasts 14-16 hours, and peaks at 3-4 hours?", options:["NPH","Rapid-acting insulin","Long-acting insulin","Very-long-acting insulin"], answer:0, explain:"NPH is an intermediate-acting insulin given twice daily, with a 3-4 hour peak and 14-16 hour duration.", ref:7},
    {q:"A 35-year-old with a normal BMI develops diabetes with positive anti-GAD antibodies, and requires insulin sooner than typical T2DM. What is this most consistent with?", options:["LADA (latent autoimmune diabetes in adults)","MODY","Classic type 2 diabetes","Gestational diabetes"], answer:0, explain:"LADA is type 1 diabetes with a delayed (adult-age) presentation, marked by positive autoimmune serology such as anti-GAD antibodies.", ref:11},
    {q:"What is the preferred insulin strategy for managing inpatient hyperglycemia?", options:["A basal-bolus regimen (basal + nutritional + correctional insulin)","Sliding-scale correctional insulin alone, with no basal component","Oral metformin only, held for inpatients","A single long-acting insulin dose only, without meal coverage"], answer:0, explain:"A basal-bolus regimen — combining basal insulin, pre-meal nutritional insulin, and correctional insulin — is preferred over other approaches for inpatient glycemic management.", ref:13}
  ]
},
{
  id: "endo-obesity",
  name: "Obesity",
  blurb: "BMI classification, the CNS hunger/satiety pathways, and the medical, endoscopic, and surgical treatment ladder.",
  flashcards: [
    {front:"How is obesity classified by BMI?", back:"Overweight: BMI over 25 (over 23 in Asian populations). Mild obesity: over 30. Intermediate obesity: over 35. Severe obesity: over 40."},
    {front:"What are the major comorbidities associated with obesity?", back:"Type 2 diabetes, dyslipidemia, infertility, hypertension, obstructive sleep apnea, steatohepatitis, and depression."},
    {front:"What are risk factors for obesity mentioned in this lecture?", back:"Certain drugs (steroids, antipsychotics), eating and sleeping disorders, and family history."},
    {front:"What are the three CNS systems involved in hunger and satiety regulation?", back:"The homeostatic system (satiety hormones GLP-1, PYY, OXM, PP, and amylin, versus the hunger hormone ghrelin); the hedonic system (food-derived enjoyment driven by dopamine, opioids, and cannabinoids); and the hypothalamus (arcuate nucleus MC4R neurons promote satiety, activated by POMC and inhibited by NPY from the periventricular region)."},
    {front:"What is the general treatment approach and initial weight-loss goal for obesity?", back:"Aiming for at least 5-10% body mass reduction, using a combination of diet, aerobic physical activity, medications, and (when indicated) procedures."},
    {front:"When are anti-obesity drugs indicated, and how is their effectiveness assessed?", back:"BMI over 30, or over 27 with obesity-related comorbidities; effectiveness is typically reassessed after 12 weeks of treatment."},
    {front:"How does orlistat work, and what are its adverse effects?", back:"An oral, pre-meal lipase inhibitor that prevents fat absorption. Adverse effects: GI symptoms, reduced absorption of fat-soluble vitamins (A, D, E, K), acute renal failure, and renal colic."},
    {front:"How do liraglutide and semaglutide work for obesity treatment, and how do their dosing schedules differ?", back:"Both are GLP-1 agonists that increase insulin secretion, inhibit glucagon, and slow gastric emptying. Liraglutide is injected once daily; semaglutide, due to improved pharmacokinetics, is injected once weekly. Adverse effects include GI symptoms, pancreatitis, and gallstones; neither is recommended in pregnancy."},
    {front:"What is the difference between primary and secondary endobariatric treatments?", back:"Primary treatments are used in a treatment-naive GI tract; secondary treatments are used in a GI tract that has already been treated (e.g. previously operated)."},
    {front:"What are the intragastric balloon and endoscopic sleeve procedures?", back:"Intragastric balloon: a primary procedure placed via gastroscopy, filled with saline and left in place for 6-12 months. Endoscopic sleeve: a primary procedure using internal sutures to reduce stomach volume."},
    {front:"What is narrowing of the gastroduodenal opening used for?", back:"A secondary endobariatric procedure — addressing dilation, which commonly occurs after prior endobariatric procedures."},
    {front:"At what BMI is bariatric surgery indicated, and what are the two general surgical mechanisms?", back:"BMI over 40, or over 35 with obesity-related comorbidities. Mechanisms: restrictive (creating a smaller gastric pouch/sleeve without affecting the intestines) or malabsorptive (creating bypasses to the distal intestine to reduce absorptive surface area)."},
    {front:"What are the gastric band, gastric sleeve, and gastric bypass procedures?", back:"Gastric band: an adjustable band with a subcutaneous port for external control — less commonly used today. Gastric sleeve (pouch): removal of the fundus and body of the stomach (restrictive). Gastric bypass: connecting a small gastric pouch directly to the distal intestine (restrictive plus malabsorptive)."},
    {front:"What is a mini bypass, and how does it differ from a standard gastric bypass?", back:"It isolates the pouch-to-intestine passage from the original digestive passage, combining both restrictive and malabsorptive mechanisms."},
    {front:"What is a duodenal bypass, and what does it achieve?", back:"Complete removal/bypass of the duodenum, producing a major degree of weight loss through both restriction and significantly reduced absorption."}
  ],
  quiz: [
    {q:"What BMI threshold defines overweight in an Asian patient, according to this lecture, and how does it differ from the general threshold?", options:["Over 23, versus over 25 in the general population","Over 30, versus over 25 in the general population","Over 40, versus over 35 in the general population","The threshold is identical across all populations"], answer:0, explain:"This lecture gives a lower overweight threshold for Asian populations (BMI >23) compared to the general threshold (BMI >25).", ref:0},
    {q:"In the hypothalamic arcuate nucleus, which neuropeptide activates MC4R neurons to promote satiety, and which inhibits them?", options:["POMC activates; NPY inhibits","NPY activates; POMC inhibits","Ghrelin activates; GLP-1 inhibits","PYY activates; amylin inhibits"], answer:0, explain:"POMC-derived signaling activates MC4R neurons to promote satiety, while NPY (from the periventricular region) inhibits this satiety signal.", ref:3},
    {q:"Which anti-obesity drug is a lipase inhibitor that can cause fat-soluble vitamin malabsorption?", options:["Orlistat","Liraglutide","Semaglutide","Metformin"], answer:0, explain:"Orlistat inhibits lipase to block fat absorption, which secondarily reduces absorption of fat-soluble vitamins A, D, E, and K.", ref:6},
    {q:"Why is semaglutide dosed once weekly while liraglutide is dosed once daily?", options:["Semaglutide has improved pharmacokinetics allowing less frequent dosing","Semaglutide is less potent and needs less frequent dosing","Liraglutide cannot be given weekly due to a black-box warning","There is no difference in their dosing schedules"], answer:0, explain:"Semaglutide's pharmacokinetic properties allow once-weekly dosing, compared to liraglutide's once-daily schedule, despite both being GLP-1 agonists.", ref:7},
    {q:"A patient with a BMI of 42 is considering bariatric surgery. Which procedure combines both restrictive and malabsorptive mechanisms?", options:["Gastric bypass","An adjustable gastric band alone","An intragastric balloon","An endoscopic sleeve"], answer:0, explain:"Gastric bypass connects a small restrictive pouch directly to the distal intestine, combining restriction with reduced absorption — unlike the band, balloon, or endoscopic sleeve, which are purely restrictive/volume-reducing.", ref:12}
  ]
}
];
